'''Roxana Saberi''' ({{lang-fa|<U+0631><U+06A9><U+0633><U+0627><U+0646><U+0627> <U+0635><U+0627><U+0628><U+0631><U+06CC>}}) (born April 26, 1977) is an [[Iranian people|Iranian]]-[[United States|American]] [[journalist]]<ref>[http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=92697&sectionid=351020101 "Iran insists against hyping Saberi case"] Press TV, deadlink 16 June 2009</ref> who was arrested in Iran in February 2009 for working as a reporter without press credentials, which were revoked in 2006.<ref>[http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=94348&sectionid=351020101 Roxana Saberi released from Tehran jail]</ref> On April 8, 2009, the Iranian government charged Saberi with espionage, and she was subsequently sentenced to an eight-year prison term.<ref name="FoxNews"/><ref name="NYT1"/><ref name="BBC1"/><ref name="WashP1"/> An appeals court  reduced the charge against her from espionage to that of possessing classified information,<ref>
*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8044193.stm Reporter Saberi leaves Iran jail], BBC News 
*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6274496.ece Jailed US journalist Roxana Saberi 'had secret document on war in Iraq'], TimesOnline </ref> and reduced her eight-year prison term to a two-year suspended sentence,<ref name="Fox-5-11-2009">{{cite news |title=U.S. Reporter Jailed in Iran to Soon Be Freed
 |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,519721,00.html |publisher=Fox News |date=2009-05-11 |accessdate=2009-06-16}}</ref><ref name="To-be-free">{{cite news |first= |last= |coauthors= |title=Jailed Iran reporter 'to be free' |work=BBC |page= |date=2009-05-11 |accessdate=2009-06-16|quote= |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8043768.stm }}</ref> and she was released on May 11, 2009.

==Biography==
===Early life===
Saberi was born in [[Belleville, New Jersey]],  the daughter of Reza Saberi, who was born in Iran, and Akiko Saberi, who is from [[Japan]]. When she was six months old, her family moved to [[Fargo, North Dakota]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Robert |last=Mackey |title=Iran Says an American<U+2019>s Reports Were <U+2018>Illegal<U+2019> |work=[[New York Times]] |date=2009-03-02 |accessdate=2009-05-11 |url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/03/02/iran-says-an-americans-reports-were-illegal/ }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=M.J. |last=Stephey |title=Imprisoned Journalist Roxana Saberi |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2009-05-07 |accessdate=2009-06-15 |url=http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1896532,00.html }}</ref> Graduating with honors from [[Fargo North High School]] in 1994, Roxana played [[piano]] and [[soccer]], and took part in [[Key Club]] and [[cheerleader|danceline]].<ref name="FNHS">{{citeweb|url=http://www.fargo.k12.nd.us/education/components/scrapbook/default.php?sectiondetailid=19180|title=2007 Hall of Fame|publisher=Fargo North High School|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> Saberi was inducted into the school's Hall of Fame in 2007.<ref name="FNHS"/>

She graduated in 1997 from [[Concordia College (Minnesota)|Concordia College]] in [[Moorhead, Minnesota]], with degrees in [[Communication studies|Communication]] and [[French language|French]]. Saberi also played for the Cobbers [[soccer]] team in both the 1994 and 1996 seasons.<ref name="Concordia">{{citeweb|url=http://www.cord.edu/dept/sports/sportsbackup/ws8nrsab.html|title=Roxana Saberi|publisher=Concordia College|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>

Chosen as [[Miss North Dakota]] in 1997,<ref name="Concordia"/> she was among the top ten finalists in [[Miss America 1998]], winning the [[scholarship|Scholar Award]].<ref name="FNHS"/> Saberi holds her first Master's Degree in Broadcast Journalism from [[Northwestern University]] and her second Master's Degree in International Relations from [[Hughes Hall, Cambridge]],<ref name="FNHS"/><ref>{{cite web | title =Roxana Saberi | work =College News | publisher =Hughes Hall, Cambridge | date =2009-04-21 | url =http://www.hughes.cam.ac.uk/news.html | accessdate =2009-05-12 }}</ref> where she played for the [[King's College, Cambridge]] soccer team.<ref>{{cite web | last =Lock | first =Beccy | title =Fantasy football | publisher =King's Parade | date =Autumn 2000 | url =http://www.kings.cam.ac.uk/development/kingsparade/issues/autumn2000.pdf | format =pdf | accessdate =2009-05-12 }}</ref> She was working on another Masters Degree in Iranian Studies at the time of her arrest.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8000522.stm "Profile: Roxana Saberi"] ''BBC News'' 15 May 2009, accessed 16 June 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103999681 "Iran Releases Jailed U.S. Journalist Saberi"] 11 May 2009 National Public Radio, accessed 16 June 2009</ref><!--and at which school? NPR and BBC do not say-->

===Career===
Saberi, who works as a freelance journalist, moved to Iran in 2003. She arrived in [[Tehran]] in February 2003 to open a fully accredited news bureau for the independent broadcast news agency Feature Story News (FSN).  FSN distributed her reports to a wide range of broadcasters around the world, and Roxana's work soon became familiar to the viewers and listeners of [[Channel News Asia]], [[South African Broadcasting Corporation|South African Broadcasting]], [[Deutsche Welle|DW Radio]], [[Vatican Radio]], [[Radio New Zealand]], Australian Independent Radio News, and others.  She also made occasional contributions to [[PBS]], [[NPR]], and [[Fox News]].

In June 2003, without explanation, the Iranian authorities revoked Roxana's press accreditation and closed the FSN bureau in Iran.  A second press accreditation was then issued, permitting Roxana Saberi to freelance in Iran for the [[BBC]].  In late 2006, it was also peremptorily revoked.  Roxana Saberi remained in Iran to research a book, and filed occasional reports from the country for NPR and [[ABC Radio]].  She was imprisoned by the government of Iran from February until May 2009.

===Iranian imprisonment===
Saberi's father reported that he last heard from her on February 10, 2009, and that she reported being held in detention for 10 days at that time. Saberi holds both Iranian and US [[citizenship]], although the Iranian authorities do not recognize [[dual citizenship]] and were believed to be treating her as one of their own nationals.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7921907.stm|title=Iran confirms reporter detention|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-03-03|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>

Saberi was arrested in February, 2009 for [[espionage]].<ref name="AP">{{ cite web | title = Daughter Now Suicidal  [[Iran]] | url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20090324/us_nm/us_iran_usa_journalist_1 |accessdate=2009-03-24 }}</ref><ref name="NPR">{{ cite web | title = American Journalist Arrested In Iran | url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=101306180 | accessdate=2009-03-01 }}</ref> According to one of Saberi's lawyers, she had obtained a classified document while working as a translator for a powerful clerical lobby. This had been used as evidence to convict her on charges of espionage.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6274496.ece Jailed US journalist Roxana Saberi 'had secret document on war in Iraq'], TimesOnline </ref> The document was a confidential Iranian report on the U.S.-led war in Iraq, and Saberi had taken a copy for herself of the confidential report, which she later stated that she had done "out of curiosity."<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/12/AR2009051203477.html Journalist Copied Iranian Report on U.S. and Iraq, Washington Post]</ref> At the appeals court, Saberi was given an opportunity to explain her side, and acknowledged copying the document two years ago but denied passing it on to the Americans. She apologized, saying it had been a mistake to take the report.<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/12/AR2009051203477.html Journalist Copied Iranian Report on U.S. and Iraq, Washington Post]</ref>

Saberi was first charged on March 2, while working as a reporter without press credentials, which were revoked in 2006.<ref name="BBC3">{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7919458.stm|title=Iran 'holds unlicensed' reporter|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-03-02|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> On March 13, a number of international news organisations wrote an open letter to the Iranian government, calling on Iran to allow independent access to Saberi. Signatories included: president of [[NPR]], [[Vivian Schiller]]; president of [[ABC News]], [[David Westin]]; [[Wall Street Journal]] editor-in-chief, [[Robert Thomson]]; [[John Stack]] of [[Fox News]]; and World Editor at the [[BBC]], Jon Williams. The open letter expresses deep concern about Saberi's well-being and "the deprivation of her rights:"<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.npr.org/about/press/2009/031009.RoxanaSaberi.html|title=MAJOR WORLDWIDE NEWS ORGANIZATIONS PRESS FOR INFORMATION REGARDING AMERICAN JOURNALIST ROXANA SABERI BEING HELD IN IRAN|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=2009-03-13|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7936659.stm|title=Broadcasters urge Saberi access|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-03-13|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>

{{cquote|We now ask that one or more international organizations that have responsibilities and rights under the Geneva Conventions be permitted access to Roxana immediately to ascertain her health and well-being and to determine the conditions under which she is held. If no charges are filed, we now urge her immediate release and ask that she be given permission to return to her home country, the United States.}}

After a month long period of captivity, on March 13, a family attorney was allowed to see Saberi and she was allowed to call her family.<ref name="BBC3"/> On March 18, marking 47 days of detention, the Saberi family called on Iran's Supreme Leader, [[Ayatollah]] [[Ali Khamenei]], to intervene ahead of the Persian [[Nowruz]] holiday.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2009/mar/24/iran-usa|title=Iran must free Roxana Saberi|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|author=Henry Newman and Coco Ferguson|date=2009-03-25|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> The US administration expressed its concern at Saberi's detention, dismissing allegations against her as "baseless." [[US Secretary of State]] [[Hillary Clinton]] demanded her release.<ref name="BBC2">{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7991020.stm|title=Clinton concern for Iran reporter|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-04-08|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> On April 6, her parents were allowed a 30 minute visit to Saberi in the [[Evin Prison]], where she was being held.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/7984787.stm|title=Parents visit captive journalist|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-04-06|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>

On April 8, the Iranian government charged Saberi with espionage,<ref name="FoxNews">{{ cite web | title = Iran Charges Detained American Reporter With Espionage  [[Iran]] | url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,513207,00.html |accessdate=2009-04-08 }}</ref><ref name="NYT1">{{citeweb|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/15/world/middleeast/15iran.html?hpw|title=American Journalist Stands Trial in Iran|publisher=New York Times|author=Nazila Fathi|date=2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> while the [[Iranian Students News Agency]] quoting a judge who is the deputy head of Iran's prosecutor's office, said Saberi had "accepted" the accusation of espionage.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.reuters.com/news/pictures/entertainment/picture?channelId=5002&currentPic=232&picId=9619612|title=ISNA: "Saberi "accepted" accusation of espionage|publisher=Reuters|date=2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref> On April 18, according to her lawyer Abdolsamad Khorramshahi speaking to [[Reuters]], after a five day trial ''"Saberi has been sentenced to eight years in jail. I'll definitely appeal the verdict."''<ref name="BBC1">{{citeweb|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/8005660.stm|title=Iran jails journalist as US spy|publisher=BBC News|date=2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref><ref name="WashP1">{{citeweb|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/18/AR2009041800677.html|title=Iran jails U.S.-Iranian reporter for 8 years|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|date=2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/World/-Iran-convicts-US-journalist-of-spying/articleshow/4417898.cms|title=Iran sentences US reporter to 8 years in jail|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|date=2009-04-18|accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>

[[Switzerland]] represents United States interests in Iran, as Iran and the United States do not presently have [[Iran <U+2013> United States relations| diplomatic relations]]. US State Department spokesman Robert Wood raised questions about the transparency of Iran's [[Islamic Revolutionary Court]] judicial system, commenting that a Swiss representative was not allowed in the courtroom during Saberi's trial.<ref name="WashP1"/>

On April 19, 2009, President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] emphasized that Saberi must have her legal right to defend herself. He wrote to the prosecutors: "Please, personally observe the process to ensure that the defendants are allowed all legal rights and freedom in defending themselves and that their rights are not violated even by one iota".<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8006861.stm]</ref>  It was reported on April 21 that Nobel Peace Prize laureate [[Shirin Ebadi]]'s organization, Human Rights Defenders, would defend Saberi during her appeal.<ref>Thomas Erdbrink, "Iranian Nobel Winner to Defend U.S. Journalist", ''The Washington Post'' (April 21, 2009), available online at http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/04/20/AR2009042003232.html?hpid=topnews</ref> This appointment was never completed, amid reports of objections by Iranian authorities.
On April 21, 2009 [[Bahman Ghobadi]], an Iranian film director, published a letter declaring Roxana's innocence and urging those who knew her to step in and defend her. <ref>http://www.iranhumanrights.org/2009/04/ghobadiletter/</ref> Ghobadi described himself as Roxana's fianc<U+00E9>. 

====Hunger Strike====
On April 25, 2009, the BBC reported that Roxana's father, Reza Saberi, claimed to have received word from his daughter that she had been on [[hunger strike]] for 5 days.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Saberi 'on hunger  strike' in Iran|date=2009-04-25|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8018193.stm|accessdate=2009-04-25|work=BBC}}</ref>  She allegedly discontinued the hunger strike after two weeks, for "health reasons."<ref>{{Cite news|title=Roxana Saberi interrupts hunger strike|date=2009-05-06|url=http://asianews.it/index.php?l=en&art=15172&size=A|accessdate=2009-05-07|work=AsiaNews.it}}</ref> No Iranian sources confirmed the hunger strike.<ref>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp?edition_id=10&categ_id=2&article_id=101460]</ref>

On May 10, 2009, Saberi's appeal was heard by an Iranian appeals court. A day later, on May 11, 2009, preliminary reports suggested Saberi's appeal had been granted. The court is said to have suspended the immediate prison term, and reduced the original sentence to 2 years. At the same time, she is supposedly allowed to leave Iran immediately. However, this contradicts the sentence reduction.<ref name="Fox-5-11-2009"/><ref>"Iran 'to release' Reporter Saberi." BBC News | Middle East. British Broadcasting Corporation. 11 May 2009 accessible online at http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8043768.stm.</ref>

Around 9:30 AM EST on May 11, 2009, news network [[MSNBC]] reported that Saberi's lawyer said that she'd already been freed.

Her situation was followed closely by [[Amnesty International]],<ref>{{cite web
|url=http://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE13/022/2009/en
