====Possible politics behind Saberi's case====
===== Speculations and alleged scenarios proposed by some American analysts =====
Separate news analyses in different publications have suggested two advantages to the [[Iranian government]] for the speedy conviction of Saberi:<ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/17/opinion/17fri1.html?ref=opinion "Editorial: Roxana Saberi", [[New York Times]], April 17, 2009]</ref><ref>[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-iran-journalist15-2009apr15,0,4355386.story "Trial of Iranian American journalist over, officials say", by Borzou Daragahi, April 15, 2009 [[Los Angeles Times]]]</ref>

* She can be used as a bargaining chip to obtain the release of [[US raid on Iranian Liaison Office in Arbil|5 Iranian officials detained by the U.S. government in Iraq in 2007]].  Iran is also suspected of secretly holding former [[FBI]] agent [[Robert Levinson]] as collateral against such an exchange.<ref>[http://www.voanews.com/english/2009-04-20-voa44.cfm "Iran Careful in Response to US Criticism of Saberi Case", by Edward Yeranian, April 20, 2009, [[Voice of America]]]</ref>  On July 9, 2009, the 5 Iranian diplomats, identified as Mohsen Bagheri, Mahmoud Farhadi, Majid Ghaemi, Majid Dagheri and Abbas Jami on Iranian TV according to The Associated Press, were released to Iraqi custody where they were expected to be transferred to the Iranian Embassy in Baghdad. <ref>[http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2009/07/09/world/AP-ML-Iraq-Iranian-Diplomats.html?hp "U.S. Hands 5 Detained Iranians to Iraq," By The Associated Press, July 9, 2009 [[New York Times]]<ref>  

* As a way for some in the Government to deflect [[Foreign policy of the Barack Obama administration#Iran|President Obama<U+2019>s effort to engage Tehran]].  A move by Iranian President [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] to offer a fuller defense to Saberi on appeal calls this motive into question.<ref>[http://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iCJY4lE5kHBHPnISEZo0LopbpHPgD97LP1C80 "Iran president urges full defense for US reporter", by NASSER KARIMI, [[Associated Press]], April 20, 2009]</ref>  However, an analysis in the [[New York Times]] on April 29, 2009 suggests that the conflict is not between conservatives and reformers but within the conservatives.  The article notes that [[Mehdi Karroubi]] asserted that certain conservatives own 63 ports that are outside of government control, and stand to lose money if US economic sanctions are removed.  This gives them a financial incentive to oppose reconciliation.<ref>[http://nytimes.com/2009/04/29/opinion/29iht-edsahimi.html?hpw "Iran<U+2019>s Power Struggle", by Muhammad Sahimi, [[New York Times]], April 29, 2009]</ref>

===== Accusations of a double standard of United States in treating similar cases =====

American civil right activist [[Glenn Greenwald]], while stating his belief that Saberi's conviction was improper, has pointed to the hypocrisy of American reporters who rallied to Saberi's defense but have been silent about the plight of journalists like [[Sami Al-Haj]], an Al Jazeera cameraman who was held for six years in [[Guantanamo]] by the U.S. government.<ref>[http://www.salon.com/opinion/greenwald/2009/05/11/journalists/ Roxana Saberi's plight and American media propaganda]</ref> Al-Haj<U+2019>s imprisonment received nearly no news coverage. Associated Press photographer, [[Bilal Hussein]], was imprisoned in Iraq for close to two years with no charges. Hussein has photographs from the Anbar province which contradicted Bush administration claims of the state of affairs in Iraq. [[Salon.com|Salon]] analysts accused United States for double standard in treating Saberi and Hussein's case.<ref>[http://www.collegenews.com/index.php?/article/iranian_american_journalist_released_from_imprisonment_05112009138/ Iranian-American journalist released from prison]</ref><ref>[http://www.dailytexanonline.com/opinion/viewpoint-05-12-09-1.1749124]</ref>

The Committee to Protect Journalists documented seven cases in 2005 alone in which U.S. forces detained Iraqi journalists for many weeks or months without charge or due process. One CBS cameraman, Abdul Ameer Hussein, shot by U.S. forces, was imprisoned for one year without due process.<ref>"[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2006/04/05/iraq/main1472263.shtml CBS Cameraman Acquitted In Iraq]", CBS Cameraman Acquitted In Iraq, April 5, 2006</ref>

==== Release ====
On May 11 2009, Saberi was freed from prison after an appeals court suspended her eight-year jail sentence.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/world/la-fg-iran-journalist12-2009may12,0,3372344.story LA Times, May 12 2009 - Iran frees U.S. journalist Roxana Saberi]</ref> An appeal court reduced the charge against her from espionage to that of possessing classified information,<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/8044193.stm Reporter Saberi leaves Iran jail], BBC News </ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article6274496.ece Jailed US journalist Roxana Saberi 'had secret document on war in Iraq'], TimesOnline </ref> and reduced her eight-year prison term to a two-year [[suspended sentence]].<ref name="Fox-5-11-2009"/><ref name="To-be-free"/>

